Grappling with the “Encoding style” scale

Last updated 2018-04-07

Here we look at the “encoding style” scale (Lewicki; Packet 2) in detail.

Differences across fieldsites

Mean scores by site

First, let’s look at scores for participants in each site:

Note that this plot includes both average scores for each site (in black), and individual scores for all of the participants in that site (small, colorful points in the background, which are “jittered” around a little so that you can see them all).

Looks like people in different sites responded somewhat differently to this scale. Participants in the US and Ghana responded somewhat more positively; participants in China somewhat more negatively. Interestingly, participants in Vanuatu did not respond particularly positively to this scale, relative to other sites.

Now let’s look at these differences in more detail using the “raw data” for individual questions, rather than these subscale scores.

Responses by question, by site

Joining, by = "question"
Column `question` joining character vector and factor, coercing into character vectorIgnoring unknown aesthetics: fill

I have not yet looked at this in detail, but here are a few observations:

  • Overall high responses in Ghana.
  • Virtually everybody has mistaken strangers for people they know (enco_03), except in Ghana.
  • The “rubber tire” item (enco_06) got really variable responses across sites, but that might also have to do with how frequently this kind of thing happens.
  • The “smelling food” item (enco_07) really got a lot of positive responses in Vanuatu! Reminds me of roast chickens…
  • In general, this scale seems especially vulnerable to concerns about cultural specificity.

Distribution of responses for individual participants, by site

Another thing we might be interested in is how individual participants responded: Were there people who said yes to everything, or no to everything? How do these distributions of responses differ across participants in different sites?
